         <xocs:funding-text>This paper is an outcome of a joint research project, funded by the European Commission under the title \u201CEU LIFE PROGNOSES \u2013 Protection of Old Growth Forests in Europe: Natural heritage, Outline, Synthesis and Ecosystem Services (LIFE20 PRE/BE/00011) \u2013 Strengthening primary and old growth forest protection in Europe by capitalising on World Heritage sites\u201D. Further funding was provided by the Federal Ministry for the Environment, Nature Conservation, Nuclear Safety and Consumer Protection (grant number 7129/001-2021.0003).We are grateful to the park administrations, especially Benjamin Herold from the Schorfheide-Chorin Biosphere Reserve (Grumsin), Manfred Gro\u00DFmann from the Hainich National Park, Achim Frede and Bernd Schock from the Kellerwald-Edersee National Park, and Matthias Schwabe from the M\u00FCritz National Park Authority (Serrahn) for granting access to the forests and for their help and support with information as well as on site. We would like to thank Song Ryong Mu and Han Il for their support in setting up the study sites. Our thanks also go to Ina Holst and Andrii Holovko who supported us in dismantling the measuring devices on site. PLI acknowledges the research professorship granted by the Eberswalde University for Sustainable Development. We would like to thank the Greenpeace Environmental Foundation, Germany (Umweltstiftung Greenpeace), and the ECONICS Institute for supporting our research.</xocs:funding-text>
         <xocs:funding-text>PLI acknowledges the research professorship granted by the Eberswalde University for Sustainable Development. We would like to thank the Greenpeace Environmental Foundation, Germany (Umweltstiftung Greenpeace), and the ECONICS Institute for supporting our research. </xocs:funding-text>
         <xocs:funding-text>This paper is an outcome of a joint research project, funded by the European Commission under the title \u201CEU LIFE PROGNOSES \u2013 Protection of Old Growth Forests in Europe: Natural heritage, Outline, Synthesis and Ecosystem Services (LIFE20 PRE/BE/00011) \u2013 Strengthening primary and old growth forest protection in Europe by capitalising on World Heritage sites\u201D. Further funding was provided by the Federal Ministry for the Environment, Nature Conservation, Nuclear Safety and Consumer Protection (grant number 7129/001-2021 .0003).We are grateful to the park administrations, especially Benjamin Herold from the Schorfheide-Chorin Biosphere Reserve (Grumsin), Manfred Gro\u00DFmann from the Hainich National Park, Achim Frede and Bernd Schock from the Kellerwald-Edersee National Park, and Matthias Schwabe from the M\u00FCritz National Park Authority (Serrahn) for granting access to the forests and for their help and support with information as well as on site. We would like to thank Song Ryong Mu and Han Il for their support in setting up the study sites. Our thanks also go to Ina Holst and Andrii Holovko who supported us in dismantling the measuring devices on site. </xocs:funding-text>
