         <ce:floats>
            <ce:figure id="f0005">
               <ce:label>Fig. 1</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0005">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0015" view="all">Overview map showing the four investigated German component parts of the serial UNESCO World Heritage site “Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpathians and Ancient Forests of Other Regions in Europe” and the location of sampling plots: a) Grumsin (CZ = core zone, BZ = buffer zone, NF = non-forest); b) Hainich (CZ = core zone, BZ = buffer zone, ED = forest edge, NF = non-forest agricultural land); c) Kellerwald (CZ<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = core zone A, CZ<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = core zone B, OF<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = open forest A (dead spruce stand), OF<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = open forest B (open beech stand), NF<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = non-forest A, NF<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = non-forest B); d) Serrahn (CZ = core zone, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = pure pine stand, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = pine stand mixed low broadleaved understorey, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">C</ce:inf> = pine stand with dense beech understorey, ED = forest edge, NF = non-forest) for each height level (in ca. 1.3 m and 0.1 m above ground).</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr1" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S1470160X2501043X/gr1" id="lk00005"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0010">
               <ce:label>Fig. 2</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0010">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0020" view="all">Boxplots showing median (horizontal line) maximum temperature in a) Grumsin (CZ = core zone, BZ = buffer zone, NF = non-forest); b) Hainich (CZ = core zone, BZ = buffer zone, ED = forest edge, NF = non-forest agricultural land); c) Kellerwald (CZ<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = core zone A, CZ<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = core zone B, OF<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = open forest A (dead spruce stand), OF<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = open forest B (open beech stand), NF<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = non-forest A, NF<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = non-forest B); d) Serrahn (CZ = core zone, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = pure pine stand, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = pine stand mixed low broadleaved understorey, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">C</ce:inf> = pine stand with dense beech understorey, ED = forest edge, NF = non-forest) for each height level (in ca. 1.3 m and 0.1 m above ground).</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr2" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S1470160X2501043X/gr2" id="lk00010"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0015">
               <ce:label>Fig. 3</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0015">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0025" view="all">Interrelation of Tmax in 1.3 m above ground with canopy cover and distance to forest edge in a) Grumsin (CZ = core zone, BZ = buffer zone, NF = non-forest); b) Hainich (CZ = core zone, BZ = buffer zone, ED = forest edge, NF = non-forest agricultural land); c) Kellerwald (CZ<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = core zone A, CZ<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = core zone B, OF<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = open forest A (dead spruce stand), OF<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = open forest B (open beech stand), NF<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = non-forest A, NF<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = non-forest B); d) Serrahn (CZ = core zone, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = pure pine stand, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = pine stand mixed low broadleaved understorey, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">C</ce:inf> = pine stand with dense beech understorey, ED = forest edge, NF = non-forest) for each height level for each height level (in ca. 1.3 m and 0.1 m above ground). Each point represents one sample plot; the colour of a point indicates Tmax; the shape of each point corresponds with the forest category of the sampling plot.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr3" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S1470160X2501043X/gr3" id="lk00015"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0020">
               <ce:label>Fig. 4</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0020">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0030" view="all">Boxplots showing median (horizontal line) maximum VPD in a) Grumsin (CZ = core zone, BZ = buffer zone, NF = non-forest); b) Hainich (CZ = core zone, BZ = buffer zone, ED = forest edge, NF = non-forest agricultural land); c) Kellerwald (CZ<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = core zone A, CZ<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = core zone B, OF<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = open forest A (dead spruce stand), OF<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = open forest B (open beech stand), NF<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = non-forest A, NF<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = non-forest B); d) Serrahn (CZ = core zone, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = pure pine stand, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = pine stand mixed low broadleaved understorey, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">C</ce:inf> = pine stand with dense beech understorey, ED = forest edge, NF = non-forest) for each height level for 0.1 m above ground.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr4" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S1470160X2501043X/gr4" id="lk00020"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0025">
               <ce:label>Fig. 5</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0025">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0035" view="all">Interrelation of VPDmax at ground level with canopy cover and distance to forest edge in a) Grumsin (CZ = core zone, BZ = buffer zone, NF = non-forest); b) Hainich (CZ = core zone, BZ = buffer zone, ED = forest edge, NF = non-forest agricultural land); c) Kellerwald (CZ<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = core zone A, CZ<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = core zone B, OF<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = open forest A (dead spruce stand), OF<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = open forest B (open beech stand), NF<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = non-forest A, NF<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = non-forest B); d) Serrahn (CZ = core zone, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = pure pine stand, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = pine stand mixed low broadleaved understorey, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">C</ce:inf> = pine stand with dense beech understorey, ED = forest edge, NF = non-forest) for each height level. Each point represents one sample plot; the colour of a point indicates VPDmax; the shape of each point corresponds with the forest category of the sampling plot.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr5" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S1470160X2501043X/gr5" id="lk00025"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0030">
               <ce:label>Fig. 6</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0030">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0040" view="all">Number of frost by forest category and time period in a) Grumsin (CZ = core zone, BZ = buffer zone, NF = non-forest); b) Hainich (CZ = core zone, BZ = buffer zone, ED = forest edge, NF = non-forest agricultural land); c) Kellerwald (CZ<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = core zone A, CZ<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = core zone B, OF<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = open forest A (dead spruce stand), OF<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = open forest B (open beech stand), NF<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = non-forest A, NF<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = non-forest B); d) Serrahn (CZ = core zone, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">A</ce:inf> = pure pine stand, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">B</ce:inf> = pine stand mixed low broadleaved understorey, BZ<ce:inf loc="post">C</ce:inf> = pine stand with dense beech understorey, ED = forest edge, NF = non-forest).</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr6" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S1470160X2501043X/gr6" id="lk00030"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:table xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/cals/dtd" frame="topbot" id="t0005" rowsep="0" colsep="0">
               <ce:label>Table 1</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0035">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0045" view="all">Characteristics of the four component parts used as study areas. [Grumsin; (BGR, n.d.; <ce:cross-refs refid="b0215 b0210" id="r0005">MLUK, 2000; Luthardt et al., n.d.</ce:cross-refs>); Hainich (<ce:italic>BGR</ce:italic>, n.d.; Nationalpark <ce:cross-ref refid="b0245" id="c0005">Hainich, 2010</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:italic>.</ce:italic>, 2010; <ce:cross-refs refid="b0120 b0375" id="r0010">Großmann et al., 2018; Wartena &amp; Ewald, 2020</ce:cross-refs>); Kellerwald (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0040" id="c0010">Bretón Pérez, 2016</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:italic>BGR</ce:italic>, n.d.; <ce:italic>Kellerwald-Edersee National</ce:italic> 
                     <ce:cross-ref refid="b0150" id="c0015">Park 2021</ce:cross-ref>, n.d.; <ce:cross-ref refid="b0250" id="c0020">Nationalpark Kellerwald-Edersee, n.d.</ce:cross-ref>) Serrahn (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0105 b0125 b0260 b0325" id="r0015">BGR, n.d.; Härdtle &amp; Oheimb, 2009; Oheimb et al., 2004; Spieß, 2015</ce:cross-refs>)].</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <tgroup cols="5">
                  <colspec colname="col1" align="left"/>
                  <colspec colname="col2" align="left"/>
                  <colspec colname="col3" align="left"/>
                  <colspec colname="col4" align="left"/>
                  <colspec colname="col5" align="left"/>
                  <thead>
                     <row rowsep="1" valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd"/>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Grumsin</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Hainich</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Kellerwald</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Serrahn</entry>
                     </row>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" role="rowhead">Conservation status</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">UNESCO WHS (2011);<br/>Schorfheide Chorin Biosphere Reserve core zone (1990); Nature Reserve (1990);<br/>Special Area for Conservation and Special Protected Area (EU)<br/>(2000)</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">UNESCO WHS (2011);<br/>Hainich National Park (1997);<br/>Special Area for Conservation (EU) (2004)</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">UNESCO WHS (2011);<br/>Kellerwald Edersee National Park (2004);<br/>Nature Park (2001);<br/>Special Area for Conser- vation (EU) (2000)</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">UNESCO WHS (2001);<br/>Müritz National Park (1990);<br/>Special Area for Conservation (EU) (2004);<br/>Nature reserve (1952)</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" role="rowhead">Size</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">590 Core Zone (CZ); 274 Buffer Zone (BZ)</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">1573 (CZ); 4085 (BZ)</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">1467 (CZ); 4271 (BZ)</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">268 (CZ); 2568 (BZ)</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" role="rowhead">Elevation(m.a.s.l.)</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">84–139</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">225–490</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">245–626</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">80–124</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" role="rowhead">Relief</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Staunch set moraine, depres- sions and elevations</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Shelly limestone ridge, interrupted by shallow wet ravines/ clefts</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Hetero- geneous relief, steep slopes</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Hetero- geneous relief (upsetted moraines), frost sinks</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" role="rowhead">Forest type</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Milio- Fagetum</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Horde- lymo- Fagetum</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Luzulo- Fagetum</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Melico- Fagetum</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" role="rowhead">Soil type</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Clay sands and boulder clay/ loam</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Shelly lime- stone and silty clays</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Poor gray- wacke soil, rich in silica, and clay silt</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Clay sands</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" role="rowhead">Landscape</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Clay sands and boulder clay/ loam</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Forested mountain range surrounded by pastures and agricultural areas</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Forest mid- elevation mountains bordered by the Edersee reservoir</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Lake-forest rich region</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" role="rowhead">Historical use</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Between 1985 and 1989, single-trunk use; extensive use only in the NW of the core zone around 1950</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Since 1965 single hardwood tree harvesting; since 1998 no timber extraction;<br/>last extraction of conifers in 2003;<br/>last forestry management activity in 2007</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Since 1980: selected tree removal;<br/>since 2004: no silvicultural interventions in core zones; since 2009: no timber harvesting in buffer zones; removal of conifers</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Since 1960 s: no silvicultural interventions in the core zone; since 2013: no silvicultural interventions in buffer zone</entry>
                     </row>
                  </tbody>
               </tgroup>
            </ce:table>
            <ce:table xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/cals/dtd" frame="topbot" id="t0010" rowsep="0" colsep="0">
               <ce:label>Table 2</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0040">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0050" view="all">Main characteristics of the study sites. [Sources: Personal communication with site managers.].</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <tgroup cols="6">
                  <colspec colname="col1" align="left"/>
                  <colspec colname="col2" align="left"/>
                  <colspec colname="col3" align="left"/>
                  <colspec colname="col4" align="left"/>
                  <colspec colname="col5" align="left"/>
                  <colspec colname="col6" align="left"/>
                  <thead>
                     <row rowsep="1" valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Component Parts</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Forest Category</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Approx.max. tree age [years]</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Main tree species</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Structure</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Last timber harvesting activities</entry>
                     </row>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" morerows="2" role="rowgroup">Grumsin</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Core Zone (CZ)</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">180</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">
                           <italic>Fagus sylvatica</italic>
                        </entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Old-growth forest</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Between 1985 and 1989, single-stem use</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Buffer zone (BZ)</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">180</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">
                           <italic>Fagus sylvatica</italic>
                        </entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Mature stand with dense understorey</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Between 1985 and 1989, single-trunk use (extensive use only in the extreme NW of the core zone around 1950)</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Non-forest (NF)</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">
                           <italic>−</italic>
                        </entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">
                           <italic>−</italic>
                        </entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Agricultural field (rapeseed,wheat)/pasture</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">−</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" role="colgroup" namest="col1" nameend="col6">
                           <vsp sp="0.5"/>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" morerows="2" role="rowgroup">Hainich</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Core zone (CZ)</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">200</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">
                           <italic>Fagus sylvatica</italic>
                        </entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Old-growth forest</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Since 1965 single hardwood tree harvesting; since 1998 no timber extraction;last extraction of conifers in 2003;last forestry management activity in 2007</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Buffer zone (BZ)</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">200</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">
                           <italic>Fagus sylvatica</italic>
                        </entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Mature stand with relatively dense understorey</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Since 1965 single hardwood tree harvesting; since 1998 no timber extraction;last extraction of conifers in 2003;last forestry management activity in 2007</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Non-forest (NF)</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">−</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">
                           <italic>−</italic>
                        </entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">Pasture</entry>
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd">−</entry>
                     </row>
                     <row valign="top">
                        <entry xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/dtd" role="colgroup" namest="col1" nameend="col6">
                           <vsp sp="0.5"/>
                        </entry>
                     </row>
